
= Introduction
This project aims to research and develop a language learning website for the endangered language Scottish Gaelic (Gaidhlig). Two essential aspects will be discussed: how languages are best learned, and how those techniques apply to a digital application such as a website.

The Gaidhlig language is endangered, and while there are accessible ways to learn it, they don't work for everyone and don't cater for all learning styles. Tools like SpeakGaelic exist, which provide structured television and podcast episodes alongside a website with quizzes on their content. Duolingo has a course for Gaidhlig\; however, it doesn't teach common phrases or words, and doesn't stick to a singular dialect during beginner teaching. These tools do work for a large group of people, but some rely on more interactive and specialised learning techniques. Such tools are rare, and most people don't have Gaidhlig speakers in their lives to help them.

The project aims to create a conversation-based learning resource. It will have set human-written units structured as a single conversation. The units will start simple, use common words, and focus on a specific topic per unit. Each unit will administer a variety of techniques and quizzes that help the language stick in a user's mind. It will provide appropriate feedback that doesn't overwhelm the user while remaining constructive. These requirements will be supported by a literature review that delves into these topics and related ones to help evolve the project idea.

Existing literature and tools will be analysed to gain industry insight into design, product experience, language learning frameworks, formatting, second language acquisition, and motivation so that the application's design is relevant and useful.

The application will be evaluated based on the literature and frameworks analysed, alongside user testing and feedback. This will all be used to write a critical conclusion on whether the application fulfils its aims.

